 when war began again. The attitude of the British government headed by Henry Addington, and in particular the diplomatic methods of the Foreign Secretary Lord Hawkesbury (later the Prime Minister Lord Liverpool) were decisive in countering Bonaparte's methods; they receive their due in this first detailed examination of events, based on original materials.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aNapoleonic Wars, 1800-1815xPublic opinion. 0aPublic opinionxHistoryy19th centuryzGreat Britain. 0aPublic opinionzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aSecond Coalition, War of the, 1798-1801xDiplomatic history. 0aSecond Coalition, War of the, 1798-1801xPeace. 4aMilitary History. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Military / General.2bisacsh  aAmiens Truce.  aBonaparte.  aBritain.  aBritish Attitudes.  aDiplomatic Methods.  aLord Hawkesbury.  aPeace Period.  aPolitical Advances.  aTreaty of Amiens.  aWar.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846152252423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846152252/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles